(50, 0, 0, -4, -4, 'Foretelling of the birth of John the Baptist and his conception.<br /> The announcement of the promised Messiah to Mary.<br /> Mary&rsquo;s 3 month visit to Elizabeth.<br /> (Luke 1:5-56). See <a href="/comm/Luke/1" target="&rdquo;_blank&rdquo;">Commentary on Luke 1</a> .', 7, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:33:54', null),
(51, 2, 1, -3, 27, 'Birth of Jesus Christ, Tishri 1, September 11, 3 BC (evening).<br /> Luke 2:1-20 &amp; Matthew 1:25a. See <a href="/comm/Luke/2" target="_blank">Commentary on Luke 2</a>. Also see footnote &ldquo;a&rdquo; on page 4 of <a href="/export/library/Old_Testament_Chronology.docx">Old Testament Chronology</a>.', 3, 'This is Jesus&rsquo; !!! year', null, null, null, 1, '2022-03-12 01:40:36', '<p>The first observation of the conjunction of Jupiter and Venus &ldquo;his star&rdquo; by the magi in the western night sky (August 12, 3 BC).</p> <p>The second conjunction occurrence of Jupiter and the star Regulus in the constellation Leo occurrs on September 14, 3 BC.</p> <p>According to Torah, Jesus is circumcized and named on September 18, 3 BC. (Matthew 1:25b &amp; Luke 2:21).</p> <p>After 40 days from birth, Jesus is presented to Yahweh in the Temple on October 21, 3 BC. followed by the prophecies of Simeon and Anna (Luke 2:22-38).</p>'),
(52, 1, 0, -1, -1, 'The magi arrive in Jerusalem, meet with Herod and go to Bethlehem to see the Christ. See <a href="/comm/Matthew/2" target="_blank">Commentary on Matthew 2</a> .', 4, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-27 16:43:26', '<p>Thanks Continual appearances of &ldquo;his star&rdquo; (see expanded notes on 3 BC).</p> <p>The 3<sup>rd</sup> conjunction of Jupiter and Regulus occurs on Febuary 17, 2 BC.</p> <p>The 4<sup>th</sup> conjunction of Jupiter and Regulus occurs on May 8, 2 BC.</p> <p>The 5<sup>th</sup> conjunction of Jupiter and Venus occurs on June 17, 2 BC.</p> <p>On August 27, 2 BC there occurs a massing of planets, (Mercury, Venus, Mars and Jupiter). This was the go sign, the magi would have headed west in a caravan shortly thereafter.</p> <p>The magi arrive in Jerusalem in early December of 2 BC. (Matthew 2:1-12).</p> <p>Joseph, Mary and Jesus flee to Egypt via caravan (Matthew 2:13-18).</p>'),
(54, 1, 0, 9, 9, 'Jesus in the Temple at age 12 conversing with the teachers of the law. (Luke 2:41-52).', 6, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-29 02:47:33', null),
(55, 1, 0, 51, 52, 'Paul is in Corinth (Acts 18:1-22) prior to returning to Antioch at the end of his 2<sup>nd</sup> missionary journey. See commentary on Acts 18:12.', 7, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-15 14:06:34', null),
(56, 1, 0, 70, 70, 'Destruction of the Temple in Jerusalem. Matthew 24:1-2 and Mark 13:1-2. See commentary on Matthew 24:1.', 1, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-14 22:17:40', '<p>On August 30<sup>th</sup>, Titus, Emperor Vespasian&rsquo;s son, after a five-month siege of Jerusalem, destroys the Temple after desecrating it; the Temple&rsquo;s menorah, Torah and veil are removed and later put on display in a victory parade in Rome. The influence of the Sadducees ends. The Pharisee Johanan ben Zakkai escapes and convinces the Romans to allow him and others to settle in Jamnia, where they found a school. See Wilipedia on the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siege_of_Jerusalem_(70_CE)" target="_blank">Siege of Jerusalem</a>.</p>'),
(57, 1, 0, 64, 64, 'On July 19<sup>th</sup> of 64 AD, a fire breaks out in Rome destroying much of the city. Emperor Nero blames the Christians and begins a widespread persecution, murdering countless followers of Jesus. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Fire_of_Rome" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-14 21:47:20', null),
(60, 1, 0, 57, 57, 'Despite multiple warnings, Paul travels to Jerusalem determined to be there for Pentecost. Paul meets with James (the brother of Jesus) (Acts 21:17-26). See commentary on Acts 21:12. While in Jerusalem, the Jews stirred up a mob and attacked Paul. He is then rescued and arrested by the Roman guard (Acts 21:27-36; 22:22-29). Paul is imprisoned in Jerusalem but then quickly transferred to Caesarea (Acts 23:23-24, 33-34).', 7, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-17 01:07:36', null),
(61, 2, 0, 57, 59, 'Paul is held in prison in Caesarea for 2 years.', 5, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-17 01:08:52', '<p>While in Caesarea, Paul appears before procurators Felix (whose reign ran from 52 &ndash; 59 AD) and Festus (whose reign ran from 60 &ndash; 62 AD). Paul then begins his voyage to Rome under guard on account of his appeal to Caesar (Acts 27:1-2). During the journey, he is shipwrecked for 3 months on the island of Malta (Acts 27:39-28:10).</p>'),
(62, 1, 0, 59, 59, 'Paul is taken under guard toward Rome, is shipwrecked on the Island of Malta for 3 months. Then on to Rome. (Acts 27, 28). See commentary on Acts 27:2.', 6, null, '62_apostle-paul-s-ship-768x397.jpg', null, null, 9, '2021-01-17 01:11:04', '<p>From the REV Commentary on Acts 27:2.</p> <p><strong>&ldquo;a ship of Adramyttium.&rdquo;</strong> Adramyttium (&Auml;-dr&auml;-mǐtt-ē-ŭm) was a port on the east side of the Aegean Sea in what is today Turkey. It was at the head of the bay in Mysia, in the northern part of the Roman province of Asia, and was across from the island of Lesbos. This ship was one of the freighters that sailed the coastal waters and traveled from port to port, which is why the verse says it was about to &ldquo;sail to the places on the coast of <em>the Roman province of</em> Asia.&rdquo; Many of the ancient ships were not well prepared for deep water sailing out of the sight of land, and so made it a practice to keep the shore in sight most of the time.</p> <p>There were many things about traveling by ship that were challenging. First, there were no passenger ships until modern times. With the exception of ships that specifically carried imperial persons, every ship was a working vessel or a military ship. Anyone wanting to travel by ship had to first find a ship going in the direction they wanted, then haggle for lodging space, which was most often just a small place on the deck.</p> <p>There were no food or provisions for passengers; any passenger had to bring his own food and wine, though some ships provided water. Especially the larger ships had the equivalent of a galley where meals could be cooked, and although the crew would always have first dibs, passengers would be allowed to cook meals during off times. Travelers also had to bring anything comfortable they wanted to sleep on, and their own covering for warmth and in case of rain. They were usually allowed to pitch a little tent-like covering at night and take it down during the day. Traveling with companions was almost a necessity. They helped each other carry enough material and food for an extended voyage, stood up for each other during the almost inevitable turf wars that would arise over the best places to camp on the deck, and watched each other&rsquo;s things if someone need a walk around the deck or was sick.</p> <p>Also, ships had no set sailing schedule. They had to wait for the right tide, the right wind, and for the omens to be right as well. A bad omen would cancel sailing. Furthermore, there were days that were considered bad to start a trip (like our Friday the 13<sup>th</sup>). No skipper would leave port on days such as August 24<sup>th</sup>, October 5<sup>th</sup>, November 8<sup>th</sup>, etc.).</p> <p>Almost always the ships would travel in sight of land. Instruments like the sextant had not been invented, and it was easy to get way off course in the open ocean, so skirting the land was usually the best course of action for ships. The exception was usually some of the large grain ships that plied the ocean and ran, for example, the trip from Alexandria Egypt to Rome.</p>'),
(64, 2, 0, 100, 100, 'Approx. dating for the writing of the Didache (see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Didache" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>).', 4, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-21 16:08:10', '<p>For a PDF copy of the Didache see <a href="https://onlinechristianlibrary.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/didache.pdf" target="_blank">https://onlinechristianlibrary.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/didache.pdf</a>.</p>'),
(65, 1, 0, -1, -1, 'Herod the Great dies. Herod&rsquo;s son Archelaus is given Judea, Samaria and Idumea; Herod&rsquo;s son Antipas is given Galilee and Perea. Soon after Herod&rsquo;s death, Jesus, Mary and Joseph return to live in Nazareth in southern Galilee region (Matthew 2:19-23), see commentary on Matthew 2:19.', 1, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-15 17:28:57', '<p>Josepheus records that there was an eclipse that preceeded Herods death on January 9, 1 BC. See <a href="http://www.ultimatebiblereferencelibrary.com/Complete_Works_of_Josephus.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.ultimatebiblereferencelibrary.com/Complete_Works_of_Josephus.pdf</a>, pages 951-953 and footnote (8).</p> <p>Footnote 8 from the above mentioned PDF copy of The Antiquities of the Jews: &ldquo;(8) This eclipse of the moon (which is the only eclipse of either of the luminaries mentioned by our Josephus in any of his writings) is of the greatest consequence for the determination of the time for the death of Herod and Antipater, and for the birth and entire chronology of Jesus Christ. It happened March 13th, in the year of the Julian period 4710, and the 4th year before the Christian era. See its calculation by the rules of astronomy, at the end of the Astronomical Lectures, edit. Lat. p. 451, 452.&rdquo;</p>'),
(69, 2, 0, -980, -940, 'Solomon&rsquo;s accession year as King of Israel. Solomon reigns for 40 years. (1 Kings 2:12; 11:42; 2 Chron. 9:30). See commentary on 1 Kings 2:12.', 1, 'Solomon''s !!! year of reign', null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-02 19:55:43', null),
(70, 0, 0, -940, -940, 'Solomon dies and the end of the united Kingdom of Israel. The Kingdom splits into the northern ten tribes (Israel) and the southern two tribes (Judah).', 1, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-11 18:23:25', '<p>It becomes important moving forward to understand the difference between the accession and non-accession methods employed for counting years. It is equally important to understand the difference in reckoning calendars (as beginning with Tishri or Nisan). For a full explanation see <a href="/export/library/Old_Testament_Chronology.docx">Old Testament Chronology</a>.</p> <p>Below you will find a chart of the Chronology expanded to represent the different calendars and accounting systems used by Israel and Judah and how those calendars and accounting systems affect how we reckon one&rsquo;s age or the years of a Kingship. It becomes a matter of perspective.</p> <h2 style="text-align: center;">The reign of the Kings of Israel and Judah post Solomon.</h2> <p>This chart represents and shows the difference between a non-accession counting system, where an event or person&rsquo;s birth year is counted as the 1<sup>st</sup> year and an accession counting system where the event or birth year is counted as 0 or an accession year and with new year following as the beginning of the 1<sup>st</sup> year. In addition, this chart demonstrates those 2 counting systems as they relate to the 2 different calendars used by the ancients, those being a calendar year beginning with the month of Nisan and the calendar beginning with the month of Tishri. Many pagan nations utilized a Nisan calendar. When the Davidic Kingdom split into the northern 10 tribes (Israel) and the southern 2 tribes (Judah), Israel adopted the Nisan calendar and the non-accession counting system, while Judah kept the Tishri calendar. There are exceptions to this. There are times when events are reckoned according to the civil calendar (Tishri) and others according to the sacred calendar (Nisan). For further explanation, see the resource &ldquo;<a href="/export/library/Old_Testament_Chronology.docx">Old Testament Chronology</a>&rdquo;.</p> <p><img alt="" border="0" src="/i/Chronology/Chronology_Chart_6a1.png" style="width:990px;" /></p> <p>Note: in year 3111 AH or 850 BC a shift occurs. Joram, King of Israel changes the accounting system of years from accession year counting to non-accession year counting. When Joram of Israel became King, the Kingdom of Judah was still using the accession system. Thus Joram is reigning 11 years in 3111 AH/850 BC, according to accession counting and 12 years according to non-accession counting. When Jehu becomes King in Joram&rsquo;s stead in 3111 AH/850 BC we see a shift, where according to both Israel and Judah, Jehu&rsquo;s reign in Israel is accredited according to a &ldquo;contemporary&rdquo; or non-accession counting system. This discrepency in the records accounts for the shift in the counting systems used.</p> <p><img alt="" border="0" src="/i/Chronology/Chronology_Chart_6b1.png" style="width:990px;" /></p>'),
