(309, 1, 0, 270, 270, 'Sometime between 270 and 275 AD. the great library of Alexandria came to its final demise. The Library of Alexandria was the largest in the Roman Empire. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_of_Alexandria" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:27:03', null),
(310, 1, 0, 262, 262, 'The library of Celsus in Ephesus is destroyed by fire in 262 AD. The Library of Celsus was the 3<sup>rd</sup> largest in the Roman Empire. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_of_Celsus" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:26:15', null),
(311, 1, 0, 499, 499, 'The Library of Pergamum, the 2<sup>nd</sup> largest in the Roman Empire becomes obsolete and deemed no longer significant during the early Christian era. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_of_Pergamum" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-21 20:59:17', null),
(312, 1, 0, 455, 455, 'Sometime during the mid-fifth century AD the Ulpian Library in Rome was destroyed. It became the most prominent library in the Roman Empire after the destruction of the Library of Alexandria. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ulpian_Library" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-21 20:57:56', null),
(313, 1, 0, 93, 93, 'Approx. dating for Flavius Josephus writing his Antiquities of the Jews (93 AD-94 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josephus" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 5, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:14:54', null),
(315, 1, 0, 53, 55, 'Paul travels to Ephesus. See commentary on Acts 19:1. Paul remains in Ephesus 2 years &amp; 6 months to 3 years. (Acts 19:8-10)', 3, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 17:16:25', null),
(316, 1, 0, -3962, -3962, 'To fully appreciate Biblical Chronology and navigate what some call contradictions, one must gain an understanding of the way years were counted in Biblical antiquity. One must also understand the differences between the calendars that were used by the Jews, and how they varied at different times. For an indepth understanding of these and additional pertinent details, download <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/jsondload.php?fil=1822">Old Testament Chronology</a>.', 4, null, null, null, null, 1, '2022-11-19 16:25:54', null),
(317, 2, 0, -791, -698, 'The Prophets Hosea, Isaiah &amp; Amos.', 3, 'The Prophets Hosea, Isaiah & Amos.', null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-07 23:10:49', '<p>Hosea begins to prophesy (Hosea 1:1).</p> <p>Isaiah begins to prophesy (Isaiah 1:1).</p> <p>Amos begins to prophesy (Amos 1:1).</p>'),
(318, 3, 0, -791, -791, 'The Prophet Jonah.', 3, 'The Prophet Jonah.', null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-07 23:11:38', '<p>Jonah begins to prophesy (2 Kings 14:23-25).</p>'),
(319, 3, 0, -749, -698, 'The Prophet Micah.', 5, 'The Prophet Micah.', null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-07 23:16:12', '<p>Micah begins to prophesy (Micah 1:1).</p>'),
(320, 1, 0, -663, -612, 'The Prophet Nahum.', 2, 'The Prophet Nahum.', null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-08 00:41:01', '<p>Nahum prophesies between the fall of Thebes in 663 BC (Nahum 3:8) and the destruction of Ninevah in 612 BC (Nahum 1:1).</p> <p>No-Amon is the Egyptian city of Thebes.</p>'),
(321, 2, 0, -641, -641, 'The Prophet Zephaniah.', 5, 'The Prophet Zephaniah.', null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-08 01:27:42', '<p>Zephaniah prophesies (Zephaniah 1:1, 4; 2:13; 2 Chronicles 34:3).</p>'),
(322, 3, 0, -641, -586, 'The Prophet Jeremiah.', 3, 'The Prophet Jeremiah.', null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-17 03:13:28', '<p>Jeremiah begins to prophesy (Jeremiah 1:1-3).</p>'),
(323, 2, 0, -609, -546, 'The Prophet Daniel.', 4, 'The Prophet Daniel.', null, null, null, 1, '2022-08-27 02:03:46', '<p>Daniel begins to prophesy (Daniel 1:1). It is not recorded how long Daniel lived or how long he prophesied. We know he was in Babylon for some period of years. We have chosen the year of 546 BC as the end of the line for Daniel to show this point. However, the ending date is unknown, it could be earlier or later.</p>'),
(324, 4, 0, -593, -593, 'The Prophet Ezekiel.', 6, 'The Prophet Ezekiel.', null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-08 16:07:00', '<p>Ezekiel begins to prophesy (Ezekiel 1:1-3).</p>'),
(325, 3, 0, -520, -520, 'The Prophet Haggai.', 2, 'The Prophet Haggai.', null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-08 17:07:32', '<p>Haggai prophesies over a period of 4 months (Haggai 1:1; 1:13-15; 2:1, 10).</p>'),
(326, 4, 0, -791, -791, 'A note on the Prophets.', 5, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-07 23:12:33', '<p>The Books of Joel, Obadiah, Habakkuk, and Malachi are undated within themselves. It is not sure exactly when these Prophets prophesied.</p>'),
(327, 1, 0, -1456, -1456, 'The Plagues in Egypt, possibly lasting a period of 6 months.', 7, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-06 00:01:04', null),
(329, 1, 0, 100, 100, '<h1><em>Early Church History</em></h1>', 7, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 17:37:03', '<p>This section of the chronology shifts from the chronology of the Old Testament and New Testament Biblical events/people and places and begins to show the growth of the church and events that occured after the death of Peter and Paul in 67 AD. Our aim is to show how doctrines changed, who was instrumental in the development of the organized church and the spread of Christianity after the Apostolic beginnings of the Church (<em>ekklesia</em>) in the 1<sup>st</sup> century AD.</p> <p>The individuals and events involved in the formation of the organized church were both positive and negative, depending on one&rsquo;s Theological position. It is not our aim to make those determinations here. The student of the Bible needs to diligently search the Scriptures and History to decide for him or herself what impact these persons and events had.</p>'),
(331, 1, 0, -3962, -3962, 'Please take advantage of the free seminar <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/play/a_journey" target="_blank">&ldquo;Journey Through The Old Testament&rdquo;</a> by John Schoenheit.', 2, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-13 17:12:19', null),
(332, 3, 0, 26, 26, 'John the Baptist begins his ministry around the Jordan River, 27 AD (John 1:19).', 4, null, null, null, null, 1, '2022-03-12 01:35:02', null);
INSERT INTO `chronevent` (`id`, `sqn`, `onebased`, `beginyear`, `endyear`, `eventtitle`, `colorindex`, `tooltip`, `picfilnam`, `piccaption`, `location`, `lastedituserid`, `lastedited`, `longdesc`) VALUES
(333, 1, 0, 35, 35, 'Approx. dating of Paul&rsquo;s conversion on the road to Damascus (Acts 9:1-9; 22:1-11; 26:12-18; Galatians 1:15-16).', 5, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-14 20:24:36', '<p>Paul&rsquo;s conversion could have taken place anytime between 35 and 40 AD. 40 AD being the latest possible dating since that is the end of the reign of King Aretas of the Nabaateans over Damascus. Paul mentions him in 2 Corinthians 11:32 regarding the time he was in Damascus after his conversion.</p>'),
(334, 1, 0, 37, 37, 'Roman Emperor Tiberius dies and is succeeded by Caligula. See Wikipedia on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tiberius" target="_blank">Tiberius</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caligula" target="_blank">Caligula</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-14 19:39:43', null),
(335, 1, 1, 35, 38, 'After his conversion, Paul travels to Damascus and then to Arabia for 3 years and returns (Acts 9:19-22; 26:20; Galatians 1:16-18). See commentary on Acts 1:17.', 3, 'Paul in Arabia', null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-14 20:27:32', null),
(336, 1, 0, 37, 37, 'Pilate is deposed as the Roman Governor of Judea and is sent to Rome. He is succeeded by Marcellus. See Wikipedia on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pontius_Pilate" target="_blank">Pontius Pilate</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marcellus_(prefect_of_Judea)" target="_blank">Marcellus</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-14 19:40:45', null),
(337, 1, 0, 39, 39, 'Antipas is exiled to Gaul and his territory is added to his brother Agrippa&rsquo;s domain. See Wikipedia on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herod_Antipas" target="_blank">Herod Antipas</a>.', 4, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-14 19:41:28', null),
(338, 1, 0, 40, 40, 'Paul meets with Peter and James in Jerusalem. (Acts 9:26-30; Galatians 1:18). See commentary on Galatians 1:18 and Acts 9:26.', 2, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-13 22:18:15', null),
(339, 1, 0, 40, 40, 'Approx. dating for James writing the Epistle of James to Jewish Christians living outside of Palestine (James 1:1).', 5, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-13 22:21:41', null),
(340, 1, 0, 41, 41, 'Roman Emperor Caligula is murdered and is succeeded by Claudius. See Wikipedia on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caligula" target="_blank">Caligula</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claudius" target="_blank">Claudius</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-14 19:42:38', null),
(341, 1, 0, 41, 41, 'Agrippa I, Herod the Great&rsquo;s grandson, becomes the ruler of Palestine. See Wikipedia on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herod_Agrippa" target="_blank">Herod Agrippa</a>.', 3, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-14 19:41:59', null),
(342, 1, 0, 44, 44, 'Herod Agrippa I is killed by an &ldquo;angel of the Lord&rdquo; )Acts 12:23).', 2, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 16:17:45', null),
(343, 1, 0, 46, 46, 'Approx. dating of Paul&rsquo;s second visit to Jerusalem, which occurs during the time of famine. (Acts 11:27-30; Galatians 2:1-10). See commentary on Acts 11:30.', 5, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-14 21:36:42', null),
(344, 1, 0, 48, 48, 'Approx. dating of Paul&rsquo;s 1<sup>st</sup> Missionary Journey (with Barnabas). They travel from Antioch in Syria to Cyprus and then on to the regions of Pamphylia and Galatia before returning to Antioch in Syria. (Acts 13:4-14:26).', 3, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-22 03:35:42', null),
(345, 1, 0, 49, 49, 'Approx. dating for Paul writing the Epistle to the Galatians (perhaps from Antioch in Syria in 48-49 AD).', 4, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 16:30:09', null),
(346, 1, 0, 49, 49, 'Paul and Peter travel to Judea for the Jerusalem Council (Acts 15:1-29). Afterwards Paul and Barnabas return to Antioch in Syria (Acts 15:30), but then shortly thereafter they separate due to a dispute over John Mark (Acts 15:36-40).', 2, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-22 03:34:41', null),
(347, 1, 0, 49, 49, 'Paul begins his 2<sup>nd</sup> Missionary Journey (with Silas) from Antioch in Syria, through the regions of Cilicia in Asia Minor, and then to the regions of Macedonia and Achaia in Greece (Acts 15:36-18:22).', 5, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 16:36:38', null),
(348, 1, 0, 49, 49, 'Emperor Claudius expels the Jews from Rome because of conflicts about Jesus the Christ (Acts 18:1-2). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claudius%27_expulsion_of_Jews_from_Rome" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 6, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-14 19:36:29', null),
(349, 1, 0, 49, 51, 'Paul remains in Corinth for a year and a half and likely wrote 1 and 2 Thessalonians (Acts 18:1, 11). See commentary on Acts 18:1.', 1, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 16:47:57', null),
(350, 1, 0, 50, 50, 'Agrippa II becomes ruler of Palestine.', 4, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 16:49:24', null),
(351, 1, 0, 51, 52, 'Paul appears before Gallio, proconsul of Achaia, in Corinth sometime between 51 and 52 AD (Acts 18:12-17). The reign for Roman proconsuls was for one year from July-July. See commentary on Acts 18:12.', 2, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-14 21:23:46', null),
(352, 1, 0, 53, 53, 'Paul writes 1 Corinthians likely from Ephesus. (Acts 19:10).', 5, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 17:15:41', null),
(353, 1, 0, 54, 54, '54 AD, Claudius dies and is succeeded by Nero. Claudius&rsquo; edict against Jews in Rome is repealed and Priscilla &amp; Aquila return to Rome and host a church in their home (Romans 16:3-5). See 49 AD.', 4, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-17 01:04:21', null),
(354, 1, 0, 56, 56, 'Paul spends the winter, of 56-57 AD, in Corinth where he likely writes the Epistle to the Romans (Acts 20:3).', 6, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 17:24:34', null),
(355, 1, 0, 59, 59, '59 AD, Peter writes 1 Peter from Rome (1 Peter 5:13).', 4, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 17:42:22', null),
(356, 1, 0, 60, 62, 'Paul arrives in Rome in 60 AD and remains under house arrest for 2 years (Acts 28:16-31). During that time he writes the Epistles to the Ephesians, Philippians, Colossians and to Philemon.', 5, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 17:52:32', null),
(357, 1, 0, 62, 62, 'Paul is released in Rome and continues to extend his mission to the Gentiles. He writes 1 Timothy, perhaps from the region of Macedonia (1 Timothy 1:3) and then he writes Titus from Nicopolis in northeast Greece (Titus 3:12).', 2, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-01-17 01:12:27', null),
(358, 1, 0, 64, 65, 'Approx. dating (64-65 AD) of Paul&rsquo;s return to Rome where he is arrested once again and is imprisoned (2 Timothy 1:16-17).', 3, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 19:30:43', null),
(359, 1, 0, 66, 66, 'Approx. dating (sometime between 64 AD and 68 AD), for Peter writing 2 Peter, Jude writing Jude and Paul writing 2 Timothy.', 6, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 19:33:19', null),
(360, 1, 0, 67, 67, 'Approx. dating (sometime between 66 AD and 68 AD) for the martyrdom of Paul and Peter in Rome. See Wikipedia on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_the_Apostle#Death" target="_blank">Paul</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Peter" target="_blank">Peter</a>.', 2, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-14 19:43:43', null),
(361, 1, 0, 68, 68, 'Nero commits suicide. There are 3 emperors that succeeded him the following year. See Wikipedia on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nero" target="_blank">Nero</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-14 19:44:02', null),
(362, 1, 0, 81, 96, 'Emperor Domitian, Titus&rsquo; brother, begins another protracted widespread persecution of Christians throughout the Roman Empire (from 81 AD to 91 AD). see Wikipedia on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domitian" target="_blank">Domitian</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-01-14 22:11:56', null);
INSERT INTO `chronevent` (`id`, `sqn`, `onebased`, `beginyear`, `endyear`, `eventtitle`, `colorindex`, `tooltip`, `picfilnam`, `piccaption`, `location`, `lastedituserid`, `lastedited`, `longdesc`) VALUES
(363, 1, 0, 89, 89, 'Approx. dating for John writing the Book of Revelation while in exile on the island of Patmos (sometime between 81 AD and 95 AD).', 3, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-14 20:05:03', null),
(364, 1, 0, 75, 75, 'Approx. dating for Flavius Josephus writing The Jewish War (75 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josephus" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 5, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:14:22', null),
(365, 1, 0, -1849, -1849, 'The weaning feast of Isaac. Isaac becomes the real &ldquo;seed&rdquo; that God promised would be the heir of the promise He made to Abram. (Genesis 21:8-13). See commentary on Genesis 21:8. Also see commentary on Exodus 12:40.', 2, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-16 18:17:18', null),
(368, 1, 0, -537, -537, 'The exiles arrive in Jerusalem, rebuild the altar and the sacrifices resume, in the Fall of 3425 AH/537 BC. (Ezra 3:6).', 3, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-11 01:44:53', null),
(369, 1, 0, -520, -520, 'End of the 70 years of the indignation on Judah. See 589 BC.', 6, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-23 21:16:46', null),
(370, 2, 0, -536, -536, 'End of the 70 years of captivity in Babylon. See 605 BC.', 6, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-24 20:43:47', null),
(372, 0, 0, 26, 35, 'Pontius Pilate is the Roman Governor of Judea. (Luke 3:1) See commentary on Luke 3:1 and Matthew 27:2.', 2, 'Pontius Pilate Governor in Judea', null, null, null, 1, '2022-03-12 01:59:48', null),
(373, 1, 0, 12, 12, 'Tiberius Caesar becomes emperor in Rome. (Luke 3:1). See commentary on Luke 3:1.', 4, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-28 02:37:10', null),
(374, 1, 0, -605, -605, 'Jeremiah&rsquo;s warning in the 4<sup>th</sup> year of Jehoiakim (Jeremiah 26:1-16).', 4, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-01-28 19:59:56', null),
(378, 1, 0, -3961, -3961, 'Why do we believe Tishri was the beginning of the year for mankind?', 1, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-11 00:18:42', '<p>Please see the commentary on Genesis 8:4.</p> <p>Refer to pages 40 &amp; 41 of The Feasts of the Lord by Kevin Howard and Marvin Rosenthal.</p>'),
(380, 1, 0, 66, 74, 'The first Jewish-Roman war. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Jewish%E2%80%93Roman_War" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 3, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-22 02:08:58', null),
(381, 1, 0, 70, 150, 'Among scholars and Church historians this period of time from 70 &ndash; 150 AD, is refered to as the period of the Apostolic Fathers. These events and entries will be coded by this yellow color in the following chronology.', 4, 'Apostolic Fathers', null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 18:07:11', null),
(382, 1, 0, 96, 96, 'Approx. dating for Clement of Rome writing to the Church in Corinth (sometime between 80 &ndash; 100 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pope_Clement_I" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 4, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 16:43:02', null),
(383, 1, 0, 132, 135, 'The second Jewish-Roman war. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bar_Kokhba_revolt" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 3, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 17:38:52', null),
(384, 1, 0, 101, 101, 'Approx. dating of the writing of the Epistle of Barnabas (sometime between 70 &ndash; 132 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epistle_of_Barnabas" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 4, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 16:48:02', null),
(385, 1, 0, 109, 109, 'Approx. dating for the martyrdom of Ignatius of Antioch (sometime between 100 &ndash; 117 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ignatius_of_Antioch" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 4, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:11:32', null),
(386, 1, 0, 125, 125, 'Approx. dating for the writing of the Shepherd of Hermas (sometime between 100 &ndash; 150 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Shepherd_of_Hermas" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 4, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:12:35', null),
(387, 1, 0, 125, 125, 'Approx. dating for Polycarp of Smyrna writing to the Philippians (sometime between 100 &ndash; 150 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polycarp" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 4, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:13:26', null),
(388, 1, 0, 125, 125, 'Approx. dating for the writing of 2 Clement (sometime between 100 &ndash; 150 BC). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Epistle_of_Clement" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 4, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:14:08', null),
(389, 1, 0, 165, 165, 'Papias writes the Expositions of the Sayings of the Lord. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Papias_of_Hierapolis">Wikipedia</a>.', 4, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:14:41', null),
(390, 1, 0, 165, 165, 'Approx. dating of the martyrdom of Polycarp (between 155 &ndash; 175 AD).', 4, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-21 17:01:58', null),
(391, 1, 0, 136, 136, 'Valentinus leaves Alexandria and arrives in Rome and opens a school where he teaches his Christian Gnostic Theology (136 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valentinus_(Gnostic)" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 5, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:15:58', null),
(392, 1, 0, 140, 140, 'Marcion of Sinope arrives in Rome teaching that the God of the Jews was not the God that sent Jesus Christ (140 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marcion_of_Sinope" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 5, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:16:49', null),
(393, 1, 0, 144, 144, 'Marcion of Sinope is excommunicated and leaves the Roman Church.', 5, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-21 17:13:56', null),
(394, 1, 0, 150, 150, 'The Gnostics begin to flourish amoung Christians. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gnosticism" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 5, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:18:33', null),
(395, 1, 0, 160, 160, 'Valentinianism begins to flourish among Christians. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valentinianism" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 5, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:50:09', null),
(396, 1, 0, 170, 170, 'The Muratorian Cannon is written listing the books of the Bible accepted as Scripture at that time. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muratorian_fragment" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 5, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:24:53', null),
(397, 1, 0, 324, 324, 'Eusebius (a historian of Christinaity and bishop of Caesarea Maritima) mentions two Ebionite groups in his writings. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eusebius" target="_blank">Wikipedia on Eusebius</a> and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ebionites" target="_blank">Wikipedia on the Ebionites</a>.', 5, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 18:25:19', null),
(398, 1, 0, 136, 136, 'Alternative versions of Christianity emerge. These events will be coded by this light blue color in the following sections of the Chronology.', 5, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:48:52', null),
(399, 1, 0, 130, 130, 'Apologists and Heresy Hunters. These related events and entries will be coded by this light green color in the following chronology.', 2, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:50:49', null);
INSERT INTO `chronevent` (`id`, `sqn`, `onebased`, `beginyear`, `endyear`, `eventtitle`, `colorindex`, `tooltip`, `picfilnam`, `piccaption`, `location`, `lastedituserid`, `lastedited`, `longdesc`) VALUES
(400, 1, 0, 130, 130, 'Approx. dating for Quadratus who is recognized as the first Christian apologist. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratus_of_Athens" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 2, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:51:57', null),
(401, 1, 0, 155, 155, 'Approx. dating for Justin Martyr writing his Dialogue with Trypho. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justin_Martyr" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 2, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 18:04:20', null),
(402, 1, 0, 165, 165, 'Approx. dating for the beheading of Justin Martyr condemned as a heretic (sometime between 163-167 AD).', 2, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 18:14:17', null),
(403, 1, 0, 175, 175, 'Irenaeus of Lyons writes his work &ldquo;Against Heresies&rdquo;. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irenaeus" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 2, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:57:38', null),
(404, 1, 0, 180, 180, 'Approx. dating for Tatian writing his Diatessaron (Harmony of the Gospels). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tatian" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 2, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 17:59:08', null),
(405, 1, 0, 187, 187, 'Approx. dating for the writing of the Epistle of Diognetus (sometime between 150 &ndash; 225 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epistle_to_Diognetus" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 2, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 18:08:45', null),
(406, 1, 0, 40, 40, 'Philo flourishes in Alexandria. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philo" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 6, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:06:54', null),
(407, 1, 0, 190, 190, 'Clement becomes the head of Alexandria&rsquo;s catechetical school. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catechetical_School_of_Alexandria" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 6, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:08:38', null),
(408, 1, 0, 222, 222, 'Origen completes the Hexapla. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Origen" target="_blank">Wikipedia on Origen</a> and see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hexapla" target="_blank">Wikipedia on Hexepla</a>.', 6, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:11:19', null),
(409, 1, 0, 229, 229, 'Origen writes On First Principles. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/On_the_First_Principles" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 6, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:18:57', null),
(410, 1, 0, 380, 380, 'Didymus the Blind flourishes in Alexandria. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Didymus_the_Blind" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 6, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-21 20:29:28', null),
(411, 1, 0, 112, 112, 'Pliny the Younger, Roman governor persecutes Christians in Bithynia. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pliny_the_Younger" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-22 02:03:19', null),
(412, 1, 0, 177, 177, 'Persecution of Christians in Lyons and Vienne. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persecution_in_Lyon" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:18:06', null),
(413, 1, 0, 250, 250, 'Trajan Decius initiates an empire-wide persecution. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decius" target="_blank">Wikipedia on Decius</a> and see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decian_persecution" target="_blank">Wikipedia on the Decian persecution</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:21:15', null),
(414, 1, 0, 257, 260, 'From 257 to 260 AD Valerian persecutes the Christains. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valerian_(emperor)" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:22:05', null),
(415, 1, 0, 64, 64, 'For extensive information on the Roman persecution of Christians see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persecution_of_Christians_in_the_Roman_Empire" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-21 19:13:36', null),
(416, 1, 0, 303, 313, 'Diocletian&rsquo;s great persecution of Christians. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diocletianic_Persecution" target="_blank">Wikipedia on the Diocletianic persecution</a> and see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diocletian" target="_blank">Wikipedia on Diocletian</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-21 20:03:07', null),
(417, 1, 0, 313, 313, 'Constantine decrees the Edict of Milan tolerating Christians. Roman persecution subsides. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edict_of_Milan" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-21 20:04:53', null),
(418, 1, 0, 306, 306, 'Constantine becomes Emperor of Rome and rules from 306&ndash;337 AD. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constantine_the_Great" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 21:21:16', null),
(419, 1, 0, 318, 318, 'Bishop Alexander deposed Arius in Alexandria. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arius" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 3, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-21 19:58:53', null),
(420, 1, 0, 335, 335, 'The Council of Tyre where Athanasius is exiled for beating and kidnapping Christians and burning churches. <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Athanasius_of_Alexandria" target="_blank">See Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 10, '2021-02-21 20:10:01', null),
(421, 1, 0, 339, 339, 'Augustus Constantius (an Arian Christian) exiles Athanasius. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constantius_II" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-22 00:48:19', null),
(422, 1, 0, 353, 353, 'Constantius becomes sole emperor in Rome.', 1, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 21:19:23', null),
(423, 1, 0, 356, 356, 'Emperor Constantius exiles Athanasius a second time.', 1, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 21:20:26', null),
(424, 1, 0, 362, 362, 'Emperor Julian exiles Athanasius. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Julian_(emperor)" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 21:21:43', null),
(425, 1, 0, 365, 365, 'Emperor Valens exiles Athanasius. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valens" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 21:22:06', null),
(426, 1, 0, 379, 379, 'Nicene Emperor Theodosius becomes emperor of Rome and makes Nicene Christianity the State religion. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theodosius_I" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 21:22:46', null),
(427, 1, 0, 381, 381, 'The First Constantinople Council declares the Holy Spirit to be God alongside The Father and The Son. See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Council_of_Constantinople" target="_blank">Wikipedia</a>.', 1, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-22 00:40:23', null),
(428, 1, 0, 285, 285, 'Anthony the Great becomes an anchorite Monk (he is later referred to as the father of all monks). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anthony_the_Great" target="_blank">Wikipedia on Anthony the Great</a> and see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anchorite" target="_blank">Wikipedia on anchorite Monks</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 1, '2021-02-22 00:41:28', null),
(429, 1, 0, 320, 320, 'Approx. dating for Pachomius establishing the first cenobite monastery (sometime between 318 &ndash; 323 AD). See <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pachomius_the_Great" target="_blank">Wikipedia on Pachomius</a> and see <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cenobitic_monasticism" target="_blank">Wikipedia on cenobite monks</a>.', 7, null, null, null, null, 9, '2021-02-21 21:35:55', null);
